# user-config.md template (project-context v0.7.0, schema 0.5)

This file is a **template**. It ships in `config/` inside the `.skill` archive. The project-context skill renders it into the operator's project space as `user-config.md` on first invocation if the project does not already have one. The operator then populates the `[tbd]` placeholders.

`user-config.md` is operator-editable. On filesystem platforms it lives in `config/`; on flat platforms (Claude.ai, ChatGPT) the operator uploads it and the skill reads it by base name (`user-config.md`). The skill never reads it by a hardcoded `config/` path.

**To configure this file:** load it and ask the assistant to walk you through it. The assistant runs the shared interview in `references/configure.md` and uses the FIELD GUIDE comments below. Config regeneration always produces a diff for your approval before saving; it never overwrites silently. Changes to governance fields (`default_sensitivity`) are flagged compliance-relevant in the change summary.

Resolution order at runtime: `user-config.md` (this file's render) > `org-config.md` > skill defaults in `references/defaults.md`.

The skill never writes to `user-config.md` outside the operator-approved configure flow. It is operator-owned.

## What goes in user-config.md

The fields below are the current schema for the user configuration layer. The schema_version on a rendered `user-config.md` is `"0.5"`, `_managed_by` is `project-context-skill`, and the schema 0.5 config header (`config_editable`, `configure_with`) is present.

```yaml
---
schema_version: "0.5"
_managed_by: project-context-skill
config_type: user
config_editable: true
configure_with: references/configure.md
---

# ============================================================
# project-context — user configuration (v0.7.0, schema 0.5)
# ============================================================
# Populate the [tbd] fields. Fields with values shown are skill
# defaults; override them only if you want different behavior.
# To reconfigure, load this file and ask to be walked through it
# (the assistant runs references/configure.md). Reload by
# re-uploading this file to your Project.
# ============================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# operator
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Identity used in audit-trail fields the skill writes
# (audit.approved_by, declared_by stamps, etc.).
#
# primary_name (REQUIRED): your full name as you want it to
#   appear on records you approve. The skill does not pull
#   this from the platform; you declare it here.
# preferred_aliases (OPTIONAL): alternative spellings or
#   short-forms the skill may use when space is tight in
#   rendered briefs.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
operator:
  primary_name: "[tbd]"
  preferred_aliases: []


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# defaults
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Cross-project defaults the skill applies when not overridden
# by org-config or chat-time instructions.
#
# hub_project_name (REQUIRED): the name of your Hub project as
#   it appears in your AI workspace project list. The skill
#   stamps this into spoke topology blocks as hub_reference.
# current_hub_version: the Hub instructions version you are
#   currently aligned with. Updated by the skill on every Hub
#   interaction. Operator may override at first install.
# preferred_platform (REQUIRED): which hosted AI surface you
#   use as your primary. Drives platform-specific behavior
#   loaded from platform-specific-parameters.md.
#   One of: claude-ai | codex | chatgpt-enterprise | m365-copilot
# -----------------------------------------------------------
defaults:
  hub_project_name: "[tbd]"
  current_hub_version: "[tbd]"
  preferred_platform: "claude-ai"


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# conventions
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Stylistic conventions the skill applies when generating new
# content. Skill defaults are shown; override only to diverge.
#
# date_format: ISO 8601 date format. "YYYY-MM-DD" is the
#   skill default and only currently supported value.
# filename_slug_style: slug style for skill-generated
#   filenames. "kebab-case" is the default.
# em_dashes_allowed: whether the skill is permitted to use
#   em dashes in generated prose. Default false (operator
#   preference of the parent vision doc).
# preferred_table_density: how tightly the skill packs
#   tables in operator briefs.
#   One of: high | medium | low
# default_response_register: tonal register the skill applies
#   to operator-facing prose.
#   One of: strategic-peer | professor | collaborative
# -----------------------------------------------------------
conventions:
  date_format: "YYYY-MM-DD"
  filename_slug_style: "kebab-case"
  em_dashes_allowed: false
  preferred_table_density: "high"
  default_response_register: "strategic-peer"


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# privacy
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Privacy posture applied to skill-written files.
#
# default_sensitivity: the default sensitivity label the skill
#   stamps onto frontmatter of new files unless overridden by
#   org-config or chat-time instructions.
#   One of: open | internal | confidential | restricted
#   (governance field: changes are flagged compliance-relevant)
# auto_redact_pii: whether the skill may auto-redact PII it
#   detects in conversation content. Default false; the
#   operator must explicitly opt in to any auto-redaction.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
privacy:
  default_sensitivity: "internal"
  auto_redact_pii: false


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# contact
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Where feedback about the skill's behavior should be routed.
# Free-form: a URL, email, Slack channel, or null.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
contact:
  feedback_channel: "[tbd]"
```

## Required fields

The following fields are REQUIRED and must be populated before the rendered `user-config.md` is considered complete:

- `operator.primary_name`
- `defaults.hub_project_name`
- `defaults.preferred_platform`

A rendered file with any required field still set to `[tbd]` is permitted (the skill operates with placeholder values) but emits a pre-flight note: "user-config.md has unpopulated required fields: [list]. Populate to complete personalization."

## What does not belong in user-config.md

- Anything specific to a single chat session — use chat-time instructions instead.
- Anything that would change schema validity. The fields above are part of the schema 0.5 contract for `config_type: user` files.
- Secrets or credentials. The skill does not need them, and `user-config.md` may end up in shared infrastructure.

## Cross-skill convention

This file's format — Linux-conf-style markdown with a fenced YAML body, kebab-case keys, every field documented with rationale — is the canonical example of the **user-config cross-skill convention**, and its placement in `config/` is the canonical example of the **config/references separation** (operator-editable in `config/`, skill-owned in `references/`). Both are proposed conventions, ratified by adoption in project-context and the session-handoff sister skill. Interview mechanics are owned once by `references/configure.md`, not duplicated here.
